# Requirements: __PROJECT_NAME__

> Updated on: __DATE__
>
> This document covers what / why, not how.

## 1. Summary

[Deliver a command-line-first tool so users can complete the core task through commands, flags, and configuration, with clear output and predictable exit status.]

## 2. User Stories

- `US-001` As a terminal user, I want to complete the core action with a clear command so I can improve my daily workflow efficiency
- `US-002` As someone maintaining automation scripts, I want stable output and clear exit codes so I can integrate the tool into pipelines or shell scripts

## 3. Functional Requirements

| ID | Description | Why it matters | Priority |
|---|---|---|---|
| `FR-001` | Users can trigger the core flow through commands, flags, and configuration | Makes the tool usable in both terminal workflows and automation scripts | H |
| `FR-002` | The tool provides clear output, actionable error messages, and non-zero exit codes on failure | Allows both humans and scripts to judge execution results reliably | H |

## 4. Non-Functional Requirements

| ID | Description | How to measure |
|---|---|---|
| `NFR-001` | Common commands start producing visible output quickly on the target machine | Measure startup time and time to first visible output |
| `NFR-002` | Default output is readable in a terminal while still preserving a stable format for automation when needed | Validate by human review and script parsing |

## 5. Acceptance Criteria

| ID | Requirement | Acceptance condition |
|---|---|---|
| `AC-001` | `FR-001` | When users follow the help output and pass valid flags, the core flow runs successfully |
| `AC-002` | `FR-002` | On failure, the tool prints actionable guidance and exits with a non-zero status |

## 6. Priorities and Version Boundaries

| Requirement | Priority | Target version | Notes |
|---|---|---|---|
| `FR-001` | H | V1 | Without a runnable command entry point, the CLI product does not exist |
| `FR-002` | H | V1 | Output and exit codes determine whether the CLI is usable in automation |

## 7. Out of Scope

- Graphical web management interfaces
- Long-running background scheduling services

## 8. External Dependencies and Constraints

- Shell environment and target operating system
- Local config files, environment variables, or credential-handling constraints
- Remote APIs, file systems, or external command dependencies

## 8.1 Beginner Fill-In Prompts

If you are not sure how to write this yet, answer these first:

| Question | Why it matters |
|---|---|
| What is the first command and flag combination that must work? | This defines the V1 core value |
| Is the tool mainly for humans or for automation pipelines? | This shapes output and exit-code expectations |
| Is machine-readable output such as JSON required? | This affects requirements and acceptance criteria |
| Will the tool perform destructive actions such as delete, overwrite, or deploy? | This changes confirmation and safety requirements |
| Which operating systems and shells are targeted? | This defines compatibility expectations |

## 8.2 Copyable V1 Example

For a common automation CLI, you can start with:

- V1 command: one most-used command with the minimum required flags
- V1 output: clear stdout / stderr boundaries, success / failure exit codes, and `--help`
- V1 safety: confirmation or dry-run for delete, overwrite, or deploy actions
- V2 candidates: interactive UI, batch subcommands, plugin systems, remote sync

## 9. Requirements Checklist

- Every `FR-*` can be verified on its own
- Every high-priority requirement maps to at least one `AC-*`
- This document does not contain stack, database, component, or implementation details
- A reader should understand what the project does without reading code

## 10. Open Questions

- What is the first command and flag combination that must work?
- Is machine-readable output such as JSON required?
- Will the tool perform destructive actions, and if so, how should confirmation work?

## 10.1 Common Mistakes

Wrong:

- "Write a Go CLI, add Cobra first, then build the deploy subcommand."

Better:

- "Users can run a command to perform one deployment check and clearly understand success, failure, and the next action."

